entry.title: Update ProxyDelegate to handle proxy chains
entry.content:
ProxyDelegate handles both proxy failure, and headers sent to specific

proxies. Instead of getting a ProxyServer, it now gets a ProxyChain with

an index indicating the specific server involved. This allows

implementers to recognize either the full chain (e.g., for fallback from

chain to chain) or a specific server (e.g., to send authorization

headers to that server).



The NetworkServiceProxyDelegate::Observer, which has many of the same

methods, remains in terms of ProxyServer; this will be addressed in a

further CL.

entry.title: Begin adding ProxyChains
entry.content:
A ProxyChain represents a series of proxies to connect one-to-the-next.



This CL begins by adding a new ProxyChain class which is always a chain

of length 1, and updating ProxyList to contain a list of ProxyChains. To

maintain compatibility, all existing ProxyServer-related ProxyList

methods remain.



The trickiest of these was `GetAll`, since it is `const` and returns a

reference to a vector. Supporting this requires maintaining a parallel

vector of ProxyServers. Once the `GetAll` is removed, this field can be

removed as well.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Skip annotating match rather than return early when not
entry.content:
found in history DB.



Previously, when a match's destination_url was not found in the db,

the history annotator would return early. However, this was called in

a loop that iterated over multiple matches. This meant that the rest of

matches in the resul would not get the chance to be annotated, even if

the signals were available. This might have led to lower coverage for

the history scoring signals than is actually possible with the in-memory

database.



This CL fixes this issue and updates the unit test to check for this

situation.

entry.title: Remove PrefetchService::prefetch_ready_to_serve_
entry.content:
This CL removes `PrefetchService::prefetch_ready_to_serve_`

and thus the requirements for serving via

`PrefetchDocumentManager::DidStartNavigation()` ->

`PrefetchService::PrepareToServe()` -> `prefetch_ready_to_serve_`.



The major checks contributing to the `prefetch_ready_to_serve_`

has already removed during the effort of https://crbug.com/1448731,

and thus the matching behavior isn't conceptually affected,

while there can be minor differences.



This enables serving PrefetchContainer in the cases that

haven't been going through corresponding `DidStartNavigation()`

calls, e.g. https://crbug.com/1432886.

Such cases are still Document-scoped, because of

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4919824.

They are not benefited by the early cookie copy starting

in `PrefetchDocumentManager::DidStartNavigation()`, but

anyway it's better than not serving.

entry.title: [//gpu] Add ConvertYUVAMailboxesToTexture() API
entry.content:
We will use this API to implement one-copy VideoFrame->WebGL texture

upload for legacy multiplanar SharedImage and pure software

VideoFrames (currently these cases go through legacy mailboxes to

implement 1-copy VideoFrame->WebGL texture upload).



The underlying implementation in copy_shared_image_helper.cc will

follow that of ConvertYUVAMailboxesToRGB(), but adapted as necessary to

match CopySharedImageToGLTexture(). As of this CL it is stubbed out. We

will implement this method only for the passthrough decoder, as the

implementation relies on doing service-side GL operations via Skia, and

manually saving/restoring WebGL's service-side GL state is not worth it

considering that the validating decoder will shortly be used only on

Android, which has the 1-copy path disabled.

entry.title: [Read Anything] PDF Integration
entry.content:
PDFs are structured differently than ordinary webpages. Actual PDF

contents are stored in a PDF iframe. And this iframe is in its own web

contents that are separate from the main web contents we are already

observing.



In order to get PDFs working with reading mode, this CL does two main

things:

1. Enable accessibility on the PDF web contents so we can receive

information about the PDF iframe.

2. Send the PDF iframe to the distiller so we can extract the content

for reading mode.



This CL also replaces active_tree_id() with a non-trivial getter,

GetActiveTreeId(). GetActiveTreeId() will work the same as

active_tree_id() for non PDF cases. For PDFs, it will return the pdf

iframe (the tree we wish to distill), if found.



Design Doc: go/reading-mode-pdf-integration

entry.title: AccountManager: Use `WeakPtr`
entry.content:
Using `raw_ptr` causes a leak at test's end, because the

underlying memory is held by



g_browser_process

-> AccountManagerFactory

-> AccountManager



but the `AccountManagerFacadeImpl` is kept inside a function-local

static `base::NoDestructor`.



Change to use `WeakPtr` instead to explicitly indicate that

entry.content:
This adds a new device policy for managed ChromeOS Flex devices to

control whether detailed hardware component data can collected for

product improvement purposes. We'd like the administrator to be very

clear on what the data will be used for, and not piggy-back on other

policies that allow data collection intended for customer use.



This is Flex-only, sending hardware data, for product improvement.

Device policies should start with "Device", according to a comment in

src/chromium/src/components/policy/tools/syntax_check_policy_template_json.py

Boolean policies end with "Enabled" by convention? So our policy name:

`DeviceFlexHwDataForProductImprovementEnabled`.



Although docs/enterprise/add_new_policy.md says we need to add a

preference and register it in Local State, etc. that doesn't appear to

be necessary for Device policies.



Tested by copying the chrome_device_policy.proto to a cros_sdk, and

building libbrillo (with added accessors) against it, then using the new

accessors to check value.

entry.title: [css-nesting-ident] Avoid restart at kSemicolonToken
entry.content:
With the CSSNestingIdent feature enabled, we retry any failed

declaration as a nested style rule, relying on backing out quickly

from the failed declaration due to e.g. an unrecognized property.

However, for properties that *are* recognized, but contain invalid

values, we're currently doing unnecessary work. Consider a case like:



background: -webkit-linear-gradient(... lots of tokens ...);

background: -moz-linear-gradient(... lots of tokens ...);

background: -o-linear-gradient(... lots of tokens ...);

background: linear-gradient(... lots of tokens ...);



For each of the prefixed values, ConsumeDeclaration will tokenize

to the to capture the whole value as

a CSSParserTokenRange, and eventually fail to parse. We'll then

restart as a nested rule, which will ultimately skip to the same

again. We can avoid this by checking if we ended up

at the in the first round.



This works due to CL:4897802, which would instead stop at '{' when

it in fact *is* a valid nested rule.



Results for NestingIdentInvalidValue.html on my machine:



With this CL: avg ~57ms

Without this CL: avg ~119ms

entry.title: SimpleCache: fix lifetime of AppStatusListener on Android.
entry.content:
Previously, NetworkContext would pass SimpleBackendImpl creation

a pointer to a status listener it owns. While NetworkContext

normally owns both the cache and the app status listener, the

cache backend creation is an asynchronous process, so if the

network context was destroyed before the cache creation was

complete, and ownership of fresh cache backend handed over to

NetworkContext, the backend could end up using a dangling

pointer to AppStatusListener.



This changes to pass in a getter RepeatingCallback instead,

which checks for NetworkContext destruction before returning

the pointer.



Re-enable some tests that were flaking because of this.

entry.title: [Track Stats] Remove support for non-gUM/gDM tracks.
entry.content:
In a defensive stance (in terms of implementer burdon), the track.stats

API was only defined for getUserMedia/getDisplayMedia-based sources.

- This is a shame, because video processing is gaining popularity and it

would be great to be able to know about frame counters for these

non-device tracks as well.



Based on implementation experience, this does seem unnecessary and I

filed https://github.com/w3c/mediacapture-extensions/issues/102, but

for now this API should only be applicable to "device"-backed tracks.



It's possible there could be more implementation burdon if it turns out

that other sources are able to drop frames early (meaning, before the

VideoTrackAdapter sees the frame), because if so we need to wire up the

OnFrameDropped callback to all source implementations. But for now my

understanding is that "early" OnFrameDropped is only applicable on

real-time devices and that supporting all types of tracks would have

been no extra effort.



But until we can confirm this and convince the WG, let's align with

the spec and throw an exception on non-device sources.
